<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="ch5-section-expanding-acceleration-subsection-a-authors-note" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Author's note on the simplifying use of <m>a</m></title>

    <p>
        The derivations of the curvature terms shown above assumed the unit direction vectors were placed on Earth's surface,
        and consequently these terms are inversely proportional to Earth's mean radius <m>a</m>.
        However,
        as <xref ref="ch5-local-cartesian-coordinates-sphericity" text="type-global" />shows,
        the derivations also apply to locations within Earth's atmosphere at geometric height <m>z</m> above Earth's mean sea level.
        In this case,
        <m>a</m> would be replaced by <m>a + z</m> in the ensuing derivations
         and the resulting curvature terms in <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-spherical-final" text="type-global" />.
         It is perfectly fine to make this replacement,
         as using <m>a + z</m> is more accurate than using <m>a</m> for locations in the atmosphere,
         but be aware that most texts<mdash />including <xref ref="bluestein" text="custom">Bluestein (1992)</xref>,
         <xref ref="martin" text="custom">Martin (2006)</xref>,
         and <xref ref="holton-hakim" text="custom">Holton and Hakim (2013)</xref><mdash />use
         <m>a</m> rather than <m>a + z</m> for simplicity.
         This simplification is acceptable since the planet is much thicker than its atmosphere,
         and it especially is acceptable since the majority of atmospheric motions of interest occur close to Earth's surface
         within the troposphere.
    </p>

</subsection>